      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER III
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">M</span>eanwhile a problem
      of some complexity remained to be solved. Hugh devoted the morning&rsquo;s
      clear-headedness to vain attempts at solution. From the position in which
      he found himself there was no issue without a loss of honour. The prospect
      chafed him like a hair-shirt. If he had erred, in times past, far from the
      paths of the homely virtuous, he had at least despised the crooked ways of
      the smugly vicious. He had been the thief of no woman&rsquo;s virtue. Such
      remnants of it as had come into his possession he had paid for right
      royally. There is a difference between sinning <i>en prince</i> and
      sinning <i>en voyou</i>, in spite of the moralist. Hugh was an honourable
      man. At least, he desperately clung to such a conception of himself. Three
      courses lay open. To abandon Minna altogether, to make her his mistress,
      to make her his wife. By adopting any one of these, he would find himself
      forsworn.
    </p>
    <p>
      He journeyed up to his chambers in a denunciatory attitude of mind.
      Subjects for anathema were plentiful. His own folly in borrowing the
      £5,000 from Israel Hart; his greater folly in incurring the debts towards
      the payment of which that sum had been mainly devoted; his uncle for
      having played this April fool&rsquo;s trick upon him, and, lastly, the fate that
      had robbed him of Irene&mdash;a clause that invariably terminated his
      commination. Three solid, middle-aged city men were travelling in his
      compartment. They appealed to his fancy as potential Eliphaz, Bildad, and
      Zophar. If he had lifted up his voice like Job, they would obviously have
      told him that it served him right. The parallel put him into a good
      humour.
    </p>
    <p>
      Shortly after his arrival, a telegram came from Minna. Could she see him
      for a minute to-day? And if so, where? She could meet him at any place and
      at any hour. It was only to see that he was not vexed with her. She had
      passed a wretched night and was depressed. It was a long, impulsive
      message, regardless of the principles of condensation, and couched in
      German, so as not to become the common property of the young ladies at the
      Sunnington telegraph office. Hugh despatched an answer, making an
      appointment at three o&rsquo;clock, in his chambers. At a quarter past, Minna
      appeared, blushing, introduced by the clerk. Her pretty apologetic air
      compelled reassuring endearments. Of course she was dearly welcome. The
      whole of the dingy room was lit up with her charms. The very wig-block was
      beaming at her. She laughed happily, turned towards the object indicated,
      and seized the wig. Would he put it on for her to see? She would fix it
      herself. No, she didn&rsquo;t like him in it. He looked too wise.
    </p>
    <p>
      They had a lover&rsquo;s hour, vowed they would conjure light out of darkness
      and be each other&rsquo;s before long. A formal demand in marriage was out of
      the question. Israel Hart would not give his daughter to a penniless
      barrister and starveling poet, who owed him money. And Hugh&rsquo;s soul
      sickened at the thought of asking him. Besides he had expressed his desire
      that Minna should marry a friend of his, appropriately named Goldberg, who
      kept an extensive bucket-shop in Gracechurch Street. To inform her father
      would put an end to everything. He would carry her off and shut her up
      like Danaë in a brazen tower, into which Goldberg would Zeus-wise
      insinuate himself&mdash;this time at Aczisius&rsquo;s invitation. Hugh proposed
      a two years&rsquo; private engagement, during which period he would bestir
      himself strenuously to make his fortune. Minna acquiesced, but only with
      the outside of her lips. She was not accustomed to wait for what she
      desired. And, for the matter of that, neither was Hugh. At any rate,
      things were moved a stage further during the visit. Before she departed,
      she desired of him perfect secrecy. He was to keep it from everybody&mdash;and
      Mrs. Merriam. He agreed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall certainly not tell Mrs. Merriam,&rdquo; he replied, dryly.
    </p>
    <p>
      She cast him a quick, suspicious glance out of otherwise glowing eyes.
      Then she bade him farewell, and tripped through the door that he held open
      for her.
    </p>
    <p>
      The following day was Sunday. Although the season was the end of March,
      there had been a sudden cold snap. In the night the temperature had fallen
      and the wind risen. The morning gave the spectacle of a blizzard, driving
      sleet and snow. Hugh laid down the rough pencilled scraps of the verses he
      had been polishing, and went to look disconsolately out of the window. The
      prospect was uninviting; scarcely anything visible through the vibrating
      screen of swift, horizontal grey lines. He had agreed to meet Minna at
      noon, weather permitting, in the little patch of wood that stretched
      behind The Lindens, her father&rsquo;s house, to more or less open country. The
      weather was hardly in a permissive mood. He felt that he could annul the
      engagement with a free conscience. It would be madness of Minna to expect
      its fulfilment. But knowing that a woman in love is capable of many
      madnesses, he resolved to keep his tryst on the chance of being able to
      despatch her summarily home again. He started out, with ulster collar
      drawn up to his ears, and thick gloves, and strode fast through the gale
      along the deserted pavements. At the appointed spot in the wood he waited
      for a quarter of an hour. Minna did not come. He congratulated her on her
      common sense, greater than his own, and retraced his steps. As he emerged
      from the branch lane leading from the wood on to the heath road, and
      meeting the latter at a point somewhat nearer the Merriams&rsquo; house than The
      Lindens, he was passed by a hansom cab, the window of which was down.
      After a few yards, the trap door in the roof was pushed open and the
      cabman drew up. Hugh approached, and perceived through the side glass
      Irene&rsquo;s expectant face. On the window being pulled up, he saw her sitting
      in the chilliness of an indoor silk blouse, while by her side, huddled up
      in her sealskin jacket, was a dirty, emaciated, shivering little girl.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What a lucky chance to have passed you!&rdquo; cried Irene; &ldquo;will you do
      something real kind for me?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Anything in the world. I suppose I&rsquo;m to fetch a doctor,&rdquo; he replied, with
      an eye on her new protégée.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No. I&rsquo;ll send Jane, if necessary. Go round to this little creature&rsquo;s home
      and tell them she is ill and that I&rsquo;ll take care of her for to-day, and if
      they like I&rsquo;ll find a decent place for her. She lives with an uncle and
      aunt, who beat her. Fancy sending out a child, with nothing on, to sell
      violets on a day like this!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where do they live?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At 24 George Street&mdash;in the slums at the back of the station. Their
      name is Jackson. Come back and tell me. I&rsquo;ll give you some lunch.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hugh nodded, stepped back, gave the word to the driver and the cab started
      off. He trudged along in its wake, amused and touched by the little scene.
      He could imagine Irene first catching sight of the child, her indignant
      whipping off of her sealskin, putting the child into the cab, arranging
      everything off-hand, in her undoubting, imperial fashion. He smiled, too,
      at her unhesitating anticipation of his immediate acceptance of his
      mission. It was well that there was a woman like Irene in the world. As he
      passed by the house, he saw her figure flit quickly across an upper
      window. He pictured her stirring up the maids, getting a hot bath ready,
      and kneeling before the fire with a roll of flannel in her hands&mdash;the
      light playing in her fair hair and illuminating her face. He dwelt upon
      the picture until he had reached his destination.
    </p>
    <p>
      He found Mrs. Jackson. Her husband was not in. If one judged from his
      home, he was certainly at that moment hugging the lee-side of a
      public-house doorway, waiting for opening time. The room was filthy. Mrs.
      Jackson, if possible, filthier. Her habitual speech, as Hugh shortly
      discovered, was filthy in the superlative degree. She was also perceptibly
      drunk. There was an apology for a bed in the room; but in a corner lay
      some sacking and a bundle of rags, evidently the child&rsquo;s sleeping place.
      Hugh explained his mission; to his surprise, met with instant success.
      Mrs. Jackson did not see why she should support a child that was nothing
      to her. She was expecting a sanguinary one of her own shortly. If anyone
      else cared to support her, they were welcome.
    </p>
    <p>
      For all she cared, they could take her to a much warmer place than Irene&rsquo;s
      fireside.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s all right,&rdquo; he said to Irene, when she came down to the hall to meet
      him.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Good,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;Come upstairs for a moment.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She turned abruptly and he followed. He knew the signs of Irene&rsquo;s
      indignation.
    </p>
    <p>
      Snugly in bed, in the room that former tenants had fitted as a nursery&mdash;but
      unused now for that purpose, to Irene&rsquo;s wistful regret&mdash;her one
      sadness&mdash;lay the little girl. Irene went up to her, drew back the
      bedclothes and tenderly exposed her shoulders and bosom.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Look,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      He bent over; the flesh was livid with bruises.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I should like to go among them with a flaming sword,&rdquo; she cried, &ldquo;and
      sweep them off the face of the earth.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish you could, before the child they are expecting is born to them,&rdquo;
       he said, grimly.
    </p>
    <p>
      He sketched his visit. Irene gave but half heed. His first remark had
      struck a strongly vibrating chord.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let us pray to God that it is never born alive,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;To think that
      such brute-beasts can have a child and&mdash;oh, why are they allowed to
      bring them into the world, and given the most glorious privilege of
      humanity?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The next best privilege is to be able to do what you&rsquo;re doing now,&rdquo; said
      Hugh, consolingly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But what is it, after all? It is like trying to stop an avalanche and
      just getting hold of a handful of snow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you&rsquo;ve got your handful.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Poor little thing,&rdquo; said Irene.
    </p>
    <p>
      She tucked the clothes around her, and, after a few nurse-like touches to
      the arrangements of the room, took Hugh downstairs. Lunch was ready. They
      sat down together. Gerard was absent on his fishing visit. They imagined
      him glowering at the weather through Weston&rsquo;s dining-room windows.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What will he say to our little friend upstairs?&rdquo; asked Hugh, helping
      himself to claret.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What do you mean?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, you can&rsquo;t settle her comfortably for life at a moment&rsquo;s notice.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Irene opened her eyes wide.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you mean that he won&rsquo;t be pleased to have her here? My <i>dear</i>
      Hugh!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He smiled inwardly, but prudently changed the topic; enquired as to her
      discovery of the child. &ldquo;Why was she herself out in such awful weather?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I was taking some trifles to a girl who is ill,&rdquo; she answered. The rest
      of her explanation agreed with Hugh&rsquo;s conjecture. Driving back, she had
      seen a woman trying to get the child on its feet. She had stopped the cab
      and swooped off with her prize.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But you needn&rsquo;t have risked your own life by taking off your sealskin and
      coming home in that flimsy thing,&rdquo; he said, with a smile. &ldquo;Even St. Martin
      didn&rsquo;t do that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you know,&rdquo; she replied, with a charming viciousness, and leaning over
      the table, &ldquo;I consider St. Martin one of the meanest characters in
      history!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Some time after lunch, the servant came into the smoking-room and
      announced that Mr. Jackson had called.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He&rsquo;s a very horrid-looking man, ma&rsquo;am,&rdquo; she remarked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll go and settle him,&rdquo; said Hugh, rising.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;No. Let me. I shall enjoy it,&rdquo; replied Irene.
    </p>
    <p>
      And she departed, with the light of battle in her eyes. She met the man in
      the hall. He began to bluster. Hugh, by a turn of the passage, stood an
      unobserved spectator.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You&rsquo;re not going to have the child back,&rdquo; said Irene.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then I&rsquo;ll have compensation,&rdquo; said the man.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;m not going to give up my wife&rsquo;s flesh and blood for nothing. &rsquo;Tain&rsquo;t
      likely&mdash;we&rsquo;re poor folks and the kid earns a little.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;More shame for you&mdash;a great hulking brute like you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t mind taking five pounds.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You won&rsquo;t get a half-penny.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then out I goes to fetch a policeman.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He moved towards the door. Irene took a step forward.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You dare threaten me!&rdquo; she cried. &ldquo;You! Get out of my house and never let
      me hear of you again, or, as there&rsquo;s a Lord in heaven, I&rsquo;ll put the
      Children&rsquo;s Protection Society on your tracks and you&rsquo;ll see the inside of
      a gaol.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Whether it was the threat or Irene&rsquo;s shining eyes that cowed the man, Hugh
      could not tell. He slunk away with muffled maledictions and banged the
      street door after him. Hugh ran to meet her, his heart aglow with her. It
      was the eternal combat of Mithra and Ahriman. He broke into boyish
      eulogies. She laughed a little excitedly and wiped her lips with her
      handkerchief.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Let us go back to the smoking-room. The foul beast! The whole air tastes
      of him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have a delicious way of setting the law of England at defiance,&rdquo; he
      said, laughing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Bad laws ought to be defied,&rdquo; she retorted, full of the flush of victory.
      Which exquisitely feminine conviction he had not the heart to disturb.
    </p>
    <p>
      A little later she claimed his assistance in another matter.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s the extension of premises for the Institution,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;The plans
      came in yesterday and I can&rsquo;t make head or tail of them.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She produced the roll of plans from a corner, and spread the sheets on the
      desk. They bent over them together, and for a long time were deep in
      architectural discussion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It will take such a long time,&rdquo; she said at last. &ldquo;I wish I could have it
      all built to-morrow.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have no doubt you could, if you really tried,&rdquo; said Hugh. &ldquo;You can
      bring most things to pass.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Institution was Irene&rsquo;s pet philanthropic interest&mdash;a charitable
      organisation of which she was the founder and guiding principle. At first
      Gerard had scouted the scheme as entirely impracticable; but Irene had
      succeeded, and, devoting to it her impetuous energy, had lifted those
      around her to equal enthusiasm. Both Gerard and Hugh were members of the
      committee, and attended meetings with praiseworthy regularity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Irene rolled up the plans and replaced them in their corner.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How little we can do to alleviate the misery in the world!&rdquo; she said,
      with a sigh.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hugh smiled. &ldquo;If you could only get a lever long enough and a fulcrum you
      would move the universe, like Archimedes. But you will have to get to
      heaven first.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s just the appalling part of the idea of heaven,&rdquo; she answered. &ldquo;As
      soon as you get there you are useless, utterly and besottedly useless.
      It&rsquo;s the only terrible aspect of death, that whether there is an hereafter
      or not, you are cut off forever from doing a hand&rsquo;s turn for your fellow
      creatures. Everything has to be done in the little sphere of your life&mdash;when
      lever and fulcrum are unattainable. I wonder sometimes that I can be
      happy. And yet I am&mdash;blessedly happy. Can you explain it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He replied vaguely, so as to hide betrayal of a little pang; for he knew
      her thoughts were with Gerard. Association brought his own to Minna for
      the first time almost since he had caught sight of Irene in the cab.
      Dismaying comparisons forced themselves on his mind.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why are you frowning like that?&rdquo; she asked, lightly.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I was thinking of all the happiness you deserve.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She laughed, with a little air of mockery.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Does it distress you so much?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose it does,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Now it is your turn to explain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      But Irene, like a wise woman, dropped the subject.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
