    <h2>
      CHAPTER XX
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">M</span>inna had rushed to
      London, which she loathed, from Nice, which she adored, and was occupying
      a suite of apartments in the Hotel Métropole. And the cause of her journey
      was Hugh; wherefore she regarded him with feelings of more than usual
      vindictiveness. His letter announcing his marriage with Irene had thrown
      her into a violent rage. She had stormed at her French maid, cast herself
      on her bed and wept, and then gone off to Monte Carlo, where she did her
      best to compromise herself with an Austrian banker who had been, for the
      past fortnight, most assiduous in his attentions. The necessitous
      gentlewoman whom, for shrewd social reasons, Minna employed as her
      chaperon and companion had chosen to be shocked. There had been a scene.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;My conscience won&rsquo;t allow me to pass such things by without
      remonstrance,&rdquo; the lady had said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t pay you to have a conscience,&rdquo; Minna had replied rudely. &ldquo;I
      possess one too many of my own.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is an outrage on common decency,&rdquo; said the lady, who had a spirit as
      yet unbroken by servitude.
    </p>
    <p>
      Whereupon Minna had dismissed her on the spot, and that evening found
      herself unchaperoned. Now, she had taken a little villa on the Cimiez
      Road, with a cool white loggia and tesselated floors. To live there in
      maiden seclusion was out of the question. To provide herself with the
      excitement that she craved, without some nominal protectress of her youth
      and beauty, would be to rank herself as unclassed. But she had not the
      faintest desire to set society&rsquo;s skirts tightly drawn when she passed by,
      as did many fair and solitary owners of pretty villas between Cannes and
      St. Remo. Her dearly won fortune could buy her much more satisfactory
      delights. In a word, a chaperon was essential. For a whole month she
      sought far and wide. She offered lavish terms. Hundreds applied. But the
      ladies without conscience lacked influence. The influential chaperons
      seemed to be steeped in the crassest respectability. At last a paragon
      came within her horizon, a Mrs. Delamere, the widow of a colonel of
      artillery, a woman of the world.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;In the course of an incidented life,&rdquo; she wrote, &ldquo;I have found that
      discretion is the better part of virtue.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The distorted epigram had brought Minna post-haste to London. She came,
      saw, conquered. Mrs. Delamere agreed to deposit her conscience with her
      bankers, and to accompany Minna southward, with the briefest possible
      delay.
    </p>
    <p>
      It was five o&rsquo;clock in the afternoon. Minna threw herself down on a couch
      and turned over the pages of a novel. She had just returned from a
      solitary drive in the Park, where she had not seen one familiar face. She
      hated London. It recalled a past life of miseries. The novel fell to the
      ground as she went over the tale of them, counted for the fiftieth time
      since her arrival, two days before. She had seen no one but Mrs. Delamere.
      In a moment of utter boredom, a vestige of gratitude had suggested a visit
      to the Bebros. But she could not face the ghosts of the horrors of that
      house. The sight of the dull, coarse, kindly faces would put back the hand
      of time, and set her again among the devils. A faint back-wash of the old
      hysteria met her at the thought. So she remained in solitary state in the
      gorgeous hotel, chafing at its dulness.
    </p>
    <p>
      Presently she rose and walked with aimless unrest about the room. She rang
      for her maid.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Go downstairs and get me a couple of stalls for the Haymarket this
      evening.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The neat French girl retired with the order. Minna went to the window and
      drummed against the pane, gazing abstractedly at the busy embankment
      crossing just below, the train creeping over Hungerford Bridge, the
      flaring posters against the Avenue Theatre.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How hateful everything is,&rdquo; she said to herself. But she remained by the
      window for occupation&rsquo;s sake. Then Justine, the maid, entered. There were
      no stalls. They had telephoned. If Mademoiselle would like a box&mdash;&mdash;
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yes,&rdquo; said her mistress, irritably. &ldquo;That will do.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She had invited Mrs. Delamere to dinner and theatre. An irrational impulse
      of politeness had caused her to leave to her guest the choice of
      entertainment. Mrs. Delamere had expressed a desire to see a much
      talked-of piece at the Haymarket before her expatriation. Minna had a
      foreboding of depression. The Empire or the Gaiety would have better
      suited her mood; also a bottle of champagne afterwards in the company of
      some amusing men. As the prospect interested her but slightly, she had
      characteristically delayed to get tickets till the last moment. She looked
      at her watch. Half-past five. She waited by the window until Justine
      returned with the box-tickets.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ll come and dress,&rdquo; said Minna; &ldquo;it will be something to do.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is true that one does not amuse oneself in London,&rdquo; said Justine,
      answering the implication.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is the most odious place on the earth; I sigh for Nice.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I also, Mademoiselle. But Nice will be dull when we return.&rdquo;.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We&rsquo;ll shut up the villa and go to Aix-les-Bains for the Russian season.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I adore the Russians,&rdquo; cried Justine with conviction.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you known many?&rdquo; asked Minna sarcastically.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;When one knows one thoroughly, one knows them all,&rdquo; said Justine.
    </p>
    <p>
      The soothing charm of a long and protracted toilette enlivened by
      Justine&rsquo;s somewhat intimate account of the one Russian whom she knew
      thoroughly, beguiled the time and restored Minna to good humour. When she
      left Justine&rsquo;s hands, adorned in the most fascinating of Paris dresses,
      with her diamond star in her dark hair, and looked at herself in the
      pier-glass, she was almost happy. She was young, and to most eyes,
      especially her own, captivatingly beautiful. The ravages that the past
      ordeal had made in her beauty had been repaired by time. Her lips were as
      ripely pouting, her dark eyes as slumberous, her lazy lids as sensuous, as
      when she had first deliberately woven their glamour around Hugh, long,
      long ago. Furthermore, she had ripened into maturer womanhood.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mademoiselle is ravishing,&rdquo; said Justine.
    </p>
    <p>
      Minna sighed. &ldquo;And to think that it&rsquo;s all going to be wasted to-night&mdash;positively
      wasted.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mademoiselle will command the admiration of the whole house.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Minna laughed contemptuously. What would be the gratification of that?
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It would please me enormously if I were in the place of Mademoiselle,&rdquo;
       said Justine.
    </p>
    <p>
      A little later Minna descended with her guest to the great dining-room.
      Mrs. Delamere was a faded, aristocratic looking woman, with an aquiline
      nose and a perfect taste in dress. She looked at her charge critically,
      noticed her unabashed and somewhat inviting acceptance of admiring
      glances, and imperceptibly shrugged her shoulders. Rather than linger in
      the Bloomsbury boarding-house, where for the past year she had been hiding
      her fallen fortunes, she would have undertaken to chaperon the
      Unmentionable Person of Babylon herself. Meanwhile she intended to enjoy
      her dinner.
    </p>
    <p>
      The crowded room, the buzz of conversation, and the expensive wines
      completed Minna&rsquo;s sense of content.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am glad that you prefer champagne <i>extra sec</i>,&rdquo; said Mrs.
      Delamere, after the first appreciative sip. &ldquo;So many women go for Veuve
      Cliquot, when they can.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, and make men afraid to dine with them,&rdquo; said Minna. &ldquo;I felt sure
      that your taste and mine would coincide. Yet I had to educate myself up to
      it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The education will not be thrown away,&rdquo; said Mrs. Delamere.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Men are beasts,&rdquo; said Minna. &ldquo;There is scarcely one who can stand against
      an appeal to his own little pet sensuality. But there is no amusement or
      excitement in life without men&mdash;and so it is worth while studying
      their sensualities.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Delamere assented with a polite gesture.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you think I am too cynical for my age?&rdquo; asked Minna in her languorous
      voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Age is a matter of experience rather than of years.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well&mdash;too cynical for my experience?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Delamere pursed her thin lips in a smile.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Some experience brings cynicism; some again brings truth. It all depends
      how you are affected.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;But what is truth&mdash;to quote Pilate?&rdquo; asked Minna. &ldquo;I haven&rsquo;t found
      it, either in myself or in any one else. To weave the most gratifying
      tissue out of lies&mdash;that&rsquo;s the end of life. If I shock you, you had
      better tell me at once, Mrs. Delamere.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You look far too charming for any one to be shocked at you,&rdquo; replied the
      chaperon indulgently.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Thank you,&rdquo; said Minna in high good humour. Mrs. Delamere turned the
      conversation to the cosmopolitan society of foreign watering-places. She
      had a wide experience of men and things, and talked amusingly. Minna
      compared her approvingly with her prudish predecessor, and congratulated
      herself on her choice. The talk was so edifying that they lingered over
      their coffee, and when they reached their box at the theatre the first act
      had begun.
    </p>
    <p>
      Except on the stage, all was dimness. The stalls, the dress-circle
      glimmered vaguely with the pale spots of faces and the broader splashes of
      light dresses. Minna sat on the stage side of the box and Mrs. Delamere
      opposite. The act failed to interest the girl, whose champagne-filled head
      craved amusement. Her nature, too, instinctively rebelled at earnestness
      of purpose and the suggestion of ideals. The foreshadowing of tragedy in
      the play depressed her. Her own soul was too dark to bear additional gloom
      with ease. She yawned, rested her elbow on the edge of the box, and looked
      fixedly at the stage, while she saw her own life, and pitied herself
      greatly. She was alone. Anna Cassaba had died suddenly three months ago.
      Now she was friendless, save for this paid woman next her, whom in her
      heart she despised. She brooded over her wrongs&mdash;over the last great
      insult her husband had heaped upon her. How she hated him! How dared he
      marry? Considering her passionate repudiation of all claims upon him, this
      was unreasonable. But if men and women were always guided by reason, life
      would be as emotional as the Binomial Theorem.
    </p>
    <p>
      At last the curtain descended. The theatre sprang into light. Mrs.
      Delamere broke into well-modulated enthusiasm. She praised the acting.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It all seems wooden compared with the French stage,&rdquo; replied Minna,
      pausing in the act of raising an opera-glass. She turned, scanned the
      movements in the stalls. Suddenly she dropped the glass on her lap and
      remained staring, and grew very white.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Take my salts,&rdquo; said Mrs. Delamere, quickly rising.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Look there,&rdquo; cried Minna, unheeding. &ldquo;There he is, standing up.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hugh Colman.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The man who&mdash;&mdash;?&rdquo; said Mrs. Delamere with tactful aposiopesis.
    </p>
    <p>
      Minna recovered, flushed, bit her lip angrily. She had almost betrayed
      herself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It gave a shock to see him,&rdquo; she explained, forcing a smile. &ldquo;The last
      time was in such painful circumstances&mdash;the trial&mdash;my poor
      father.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Delamere nodded sympathy, and looked with curious interest at Hugh&rsquo;s
      handsome face and haughty bearing.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And there is the heroine of his romance with him, Mrs. Merriam. I know
      her by sight.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They were married a month ago,&rdquo; said Minna, steadying her voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;They were both friends of yours, I believe.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;He was,&rdquo; said Minna.
    </p>
    <p>
      At that moment, she saw his eyes, which had been idly wandering round the
      house, fix themselves with awful suddenness upon hers. Instinct warned her
      of the danger of putting Mrs. Delamere on the scent of a mystery. She made
      Hugh an unmistakably cordial bow, to which he responded with grave
      courtesy. Then he sat down beside Irene. The conjuncture of the parties in
      so celebrated a trial did not pass unnoticed. A whispering here, followed
      by a glance, an opera-glass levelled there, indicated to Minna the fact of
      their recognition. Exaggerating the danger, she summoned the box-attendant
      and, borrowing a pencil, scribbled in German upon a bit of her programme:
      &ldquo;Come and speak to me, to save appearances.&rdquo; The note despatched, she
      awaited events.
    </p>
    <p>
      Hugh sat down by Irene, and hated to meet the love and trust in her clear
      eyes. It was the first time they had appeared together in public since
      their marriage, the first time either had been to a theatre since his
      arrest for Israel Hart&rsquo;s murder. It had been a small event in their lives,
      enjoyed in anticipation, and up to now enjoyed in realisation. They had
      held hands lover-wise during the act, under cover of the darkness,
      signalling emotions by little finger-pressures. He rode on the full tide
      of the past month&rsquo;s wondrous happiness. Now and then his mind wandered to
      the sheltered haven on the sweet Cornish coast where the all-fulfilling
      days of their honeymoon had been passed; where the woman, shyly revealing
      her inner tendernesses, seemed thereby to regain day by day the colour of
      her cheeks and the serenity of her brow. And his thoughts flew forward to
      the journey home, to the strange new fact of not parting at the door, and
      walking back to his lonely rooms with his heart aching for wild
      impossibilities. He had risen with a laughing speech:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am going to delight myself by seeing how inferior all other women are
      to you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      And then his eyes had met those of Minna fixed upon him like a fate.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Strange we should see her on our first appearance,&rdquo; said Irene.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She is looking remarkably well,&rdquo; he returned, realising and hating the
      banality of the remark. Then he was silent. Irene noticed a constraint.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Never mind if it calls up cruel associations, dear. The past troubles
      have brought the present happiness. You must always remember that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Could I ever forget?&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She has improved in looks,&rdquo; said Irene, with a glance at the box. &ldquo;The
      last time I saw her, poor thing, she was terribly pulled down. I don&rsquo;t
      think I ever told you. It was on the awful evening of the first day of the
      trial. She suddenly appeared at our house, and, before she could speak,
      was stricken dumb with hysteria. We had to send her back to her friends.
      Strange, wasn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very strange,&rdquo; said Hugh, in a low voice.
    </p>
    <p>
      What could have been the intention of her visit?
    </p>
    <p>
      To confess? He dared not show the agitation that the story caused him. He
      rose brusquely, with a desire to escape for a moment from the torture of
      his present position. Its falseness stung his impatience. A little
      bald-headed man two rows of stalls off, who was looking with curiosity at
      the hero of the <i>cause célèbre</i>, suddenly met Hugh&rsquo;s glance and
      curled up like a shrivelled leaf into his stall. But Hugh had been quite
      unconscious of the bald-headed man&rsquo;s interest.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why don&rsquo;t you go and smoke a cigarette?&rdquo; said Irene.
    </p>
    <p>
      As he turned towards her, he saw the tender truthful love in her face, and
      he called himself a villain for deceiving her. But it was for her
      happiness. Indubitatively.
    </p>
    <p>
      Still the presence there of the other woman shed a ghastly light upon his
      honour rooted in dishonour. And Irene&rsquo;s simple statement of Minna&rsquo;s
      mysterious visit, whose baffled intention he could not but surmise, added
      a grimmer irony to the situation. Before he could reply to Irene, however,
      the attendant had edged her way to him with Minna&rsquo;s note. His brow
      darkened as he read the words. He could not refuse. Besides, Irene had
      heard the attendant&rsquo;s enquiry and explanation.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I will go and speak to her if you don&rsquo;t mind,&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Of course you must,&rdquo; said Irene. &ldquo;She will be glad to see you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hugh looked at his watch. There were still ten minutes before the curtain
      rose. There would be time for a brief interview. The briefer the better.
    </p>
    <p>
      He made his way along the line of stalls and ran up the stairs to Minna&rsquo;s
      box. She met him outside, in the carpeted and quiet passage, and walked a
      step or two past the door of her box, so as to be beyond the earshot of
      Mrs. Delamere. She held out her hand to him with an air of contemptuous
      defiance.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So you have committed bigamy?&rdquo; she remarked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;To put it bluntly, I have,&rdquo; replied Hugh. &ldquo;You scarcely summoned me to
      give yourself the pleasure of telling me that.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who knows?&rdquo; said Minna, with an insolent upsweep of her lazy lashes.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Have you anything to say against it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, dear, no. You got my letter, didn&rsquo;t you? You can have as many wives
      as the late Brigham Young, if you like.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Hugh bowed ironically. It was like her to meet tragic issues with
      vulgarity.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Tell me,&rdquo; he said, with a quick change of manner, &ldquo;why did you go to Mrs.
      Merriam&rsquo;s on that evening during the trial?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The question was so abrupt and the incident for the moment so far from her
      thoughts that she gave a little gasp of surprise and the blood came into
      her cheeks. She drooped her eyes, stole a surreptitious glance at him, and
      seeing his face very stern, hardened her heart and laughed contemptuously.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;The thing got on my nerves, I suppose&mdash;you don&rsquo;t fancy I
      contemplated murdering you in cold blood? I thought your dear, true friend
      Mr. Merriam might help me. Wasn&rsquo;t I a silly little fool?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am glad you had one moment of compunction,&rdquo; said Hugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have sincerely repented of it since, I assure you. But we need not talk
      of unpleasant things. All is for the best in this best of all possible
      worlds. I see you are amply consoled, while I&mdash;&mdash;&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you?&rdquo;.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I console myself, too,&rdquo; she answered insolently. He regarded her
      pityingly; was silent for a moment. Then he said in a kinder tone:
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Why speak like this? I should be happy to feel that you had made an
      effort to save me. For I have judged you harshly. If you tried to act
      loyally towards me, as I tried to act towards you, the fact will save us
      from hating one another.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will it?&rdquo; she echoed. &ldquo;My dear man, you can&rsquo;t possibly conceive how I
      hate you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Very well, then. We&rsquo;ll remain the best of enemies. Are you staying long
      in London?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Till the day after to-morrow. I am afraid I shall not have the pleasure
      of asking you to call on me.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I regret it extremely,&rdquo; replied Hugh. &ldquo;And now that I believe the curtain
      is up, I will say good-bye.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Won&rsquo;t you sit through the act in our box?&rdquo; asked Minna. &ldquo;It will be
      difficult to get back to your&mdash;other wife.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He turned on his heel and walked away. She looked back at him until the
      curve of the passage hid him from her view, and then entered her box.
    </p>
    <p>
      With muttered apologies to disturbed stall occupants Hugh regained his
      place by Irene. She slipped her hand, as before, into his, and whispered a
      welcome. His grasp grew tight as his heart swelled within him. Oh, God, it
      was good to have her safe and secure! But the spell of the play had lost
      its power. When the curtain fell again, he was scarcely conscious of what
      had passed. It had fallen on a highly dramatic situation. Irene gave the
      little sigh of relieved tension, and turned to him, her face lit with the
      afterglow of kindled emotion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You are enjoying it, dearest?&rdquo; he said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, yes. And you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am beside you, Renie. That is all I want in this world.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The answer contented her. She whispered a foolish word, her head near his.
      Instinctively he raised his eyes to Minna&rsquo;s box, and saw her staring down
      at him with the hard, ugly look upon her face that he had known so well in
      days past.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am afraid that poor girl is not happy,&rdquo; said Irene, following his
      glance. &ldquo;Isn&rsquo;t it strange, Hugh dear, that from the very first, I always
      wanted to lighten her lot? What a meddlesome creature she would think me
      if she knew!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She drove knives into the man. In what estimation would she hold him, if
      he told her his and that girl&rsquo;s story? He was no hero in his own eyes; in
      hers he day by day perceived, with an indescribable mingling of pain and
      pride, that he was. It was her nature to exalt any one she loved on a
      pinnacle of greatness. He had married her, allowing her to remain in
      ignorance, honestly, according to his lights; for the sake of her welfare
      alone. Now, for the first time, he trembled for himself.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t be sad, dear,&rdquo; she said after awhile. &ldquo;I can look back on it all so
      calmly&mdash;as if it had happened in a prior state of existence. And so
      must you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Love is the god that works all healing,&rdquo; he replied. And the sincerity of
      his faith comforted him.
    </p>
    <p>
      The object of Irene&rsquo;s pity soon withdrew into the shadow of the box, and
      plunged into flippant and bitter dialogue with Mrs. Delamere. The
      newspaper account of the scandal gave her scope for much mordant criticism
      of Hugh and Irene. It was a savage pleasure to tear their reputation to
      shreds, heap on invective and opprobrium, invent past meannesses and
      dishonours and treacheries.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You seem to dislike him very much,&rdquo; remarked Mrs. Delamere, smiling.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who wouldn&rsquo;t, considering his record of infamy?&rdquo; replied Minna, her rich,
      deep voice turning, as it always did when she was angered, to harshness.
    </p>
    <p>
      The smile flickered inscrutably around Mrs. Delamere&rsquo;s thin lips.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I don&rsquo;t know,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;I can forgive the woman. I should think most
      women with whom he has come in contact have been ready to throw themselves
      away upon him. He is a splendid looking animal.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you think women are beasts like men?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;There&rsquo;s not much to choose between them,&rdquo; replied Mrs. Delamere.
    </p>
    <p>
      The last act began; Mrs. Delamere gave herself up to the stage. Minna
      leant on the edge of the box and brooded over the two figures side by
      side, just distinguishable in the chequered dimness of the stalls. When
      the piece was over, she hurried her companion out of the theatre, and
      parted from her at the door. A cab quickly took her to the Métropole. She
      went straight into her bedroom and ordered a small bottle of champagne and
      some biscuits, which she consumed while Justine aided her to undress.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Has Mademoiselle well amused herself?&rdquo; asked Justine.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t chatter in that irritating way,&rdquo; said Minna snappishly. So Justine
      concluded her operations in silence, and retired at the earliest
      opportunity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Minna wrapped her dressing-gown around her and lay back in a chair, with
      the last half glass of champagne beside hen And gradually the sensuousness
      faded from her face, and her eyes grew haunted by trouble and her lips
      worked nervously. Thus she remained rigid, save for her lips and swelling
      bosom, for a long time. At last, in a vehement whisper:
 </p>
    <p>
&ldquo;Yes, I hate him,&rdquo;
       she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
    <hr />
    <p>
      <a name="link2HCH0021" id="link2HCH0021"> </a>
    </p>
    <div style="height: 4em;">
      <br /><br /><br /><br />
    </div>
    <h2>
      CHAPTER XXI
    </h2>
    <p class="pfirst">
      <span class="dropcap" style="font-size: 4.00em">F</span>or a while the sun
      of his happiness declined and the shadow of his danger rested upon Hugh.
      But presently it was noontide again, and, after the manner of men, he
      forgot the danger. The months passed and grew into years, and a wonderful
      joy came into Irene&rsquo;s sky and lit, with a new worship, her love for Hugh.
      But Minna lived in the gloom of a disastrous life.
    </p>
    <p>
      Three years had passed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Her high-heeled shoes came down with a click upon the tiled floor of the
      loggia at every swing forward of her American rocking-chair. As Mrs.
      Delamere&rsquo;s nerves had been tried of late, she rose, after some wincing,
      and prepared to enter the drawing-room. Three years&rsquo; chaperonage of Minna
      had brought their wear and tear upon the system; and Minna&rsquo;s character had
      decidedly not softened. They had, however, remained excellent friends, and
      had formed a cold, cynical attachment to each other. The pulling up of a
      carriage in the court-yard below drew Mrs. Delamere to the balustrade.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;If you are really going to Monte Carlo, you had better make haste, or you
      will miss the 10.55. There is the carriage.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Minna stopped her rocking, and lay back in the chair in a lazy attitude.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish I hadn&rsquo;t told Boissy I would come.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So do I. He&rsquo;s a bit of a cad. It won&rsquo;t do you any good to placard
      yourself about with him.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Because he tells improper stories?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;On a fortnight&rsquo;s acquaintance,&rdquo; said Mrs. Delamere.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Well, he&rsquo;s the only man I have met who can tell you them without making
      you feel bound to blush. Blushing is a nuisance. In fact everything in the
      world is a nuisance. I wish I were out of it.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You would scarcely find your way to a better one,&rdquo; remarked the elder
      lady suavely.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Who knows?&rdquo; said Minna. &ldquo;This is pretty bad. Here all the virtuous are
      deadly dull and despise me. All those who seek me out and amuse me are
      vicious and vulgar. I hate the sight of Boissy.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t you think you had better spend a quiet day here, for a change&mdash;send
      a telegram to Boissy?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, lord! I should go crazy if I sat here doing nothing all day. It is
      punishment for my sins, I suppose.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do as you like, my dear,&rdquo; said Mrs. Delamere. &ldquo;Only, if you go, keep your
      wits about you.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I can command the services of better looking animals than Boissy, if I
      want to compromise myself,&rdquo; retorted Minna. &ldquo;He looks as if he came out of
      the Bon Marché. But he&rsquo;ll give me the best <i>déjeuner</i> in Monte
      Carlo.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is getting late, Mademoiselle,&rdquo; said Justine, appearing on the loggia
      with an anxious face. Minna rose sighing, and followed the maid indoors. A
      short while afterwards, Mrs. Delamere saw her charge, attired in a
      daffodil-yellow dress and a showy straw hat, a wilderness of bows and
      flowers, drive off buttoning her long gloves.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;She is overdoing it,&rdquo; she murmured to herself, as she kissed the tips of
      her fingers to Minna. &ldquo;She will be wearing her diamonds in the daytime
      next. I&rsquo;m glad I&rsquo;m not a disappointed Jewess.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The Vicomte de Boissy, a short young man, with a small curled black
      moustache, a bad mouth, and somewhat dissipated eyes, dressed in a striped
      flannel suit and carrying a gold-knobbed malacca, met Minna as she
      alighted on the platform of the pretty little Monte Carlo station. He
      welcomed her with many compliments. She was ravishing. He scarcely dared
      hope she would do him the honour&mdash;even after her note had arrived.
      When he saw her descend from the railway carriage, he was dazzled. Minna
      looked at him with a little curl of disdain. Mrs. Delamere was right. He
      was a bit of a cad. And among such had her lot fallen. A tall, clean,
      high-bred Englishman passed her by. He reminded her of Hugh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Women are fools, aren&rsquo;t they, M. de Boissy?&rdquo; she said, as they emerged
      from the lift, and were walking across the square, bright with shops and
      cafés, towards the great white casino. &ldquo;But I suppose you settled that for
      yourself at the age of ten.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;<i>Ma foi</i>, Mademoiselle,&rdquo; he replied, &ldquo;there is no folly in being
      gracious to the most humble of your admirers.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh! I wasn&rsquo;t at all thinking of my coming to lunch with you to-day. You
      need not flatter yourself.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He pleaded for mercy, adroitly turned the conversation, touched upon the
      scandalous chronicle of the place and made her laugh. They strolled
      through the building to the gardens. The weather was a perfect Riviera
      March, the grounds gay with bright dresses. Now and then an acquaintance
      passed, generally masculine and foreign, and bowed low to her. At which
      times her companion drew himself up and put on airs of importance, which
      Minna&rsquo;s half-closed eyes were shrewd to notice. At last she grew weary of
      walking. She asked him sharply whether they were ever going to lunch. He
      overwhelmed her with apologies, conducted her back through the casino and
      across the square to the Hôtel de Paris, where he had reserved a table.
      There, amid the popping of champagne corks, the cosmopolitan chatter, the
      sparkle of the scene, and the <i>grivois</i> wit of her host, Minna threw
      off her sarcastic mood and jested recklessly. She was only capable of
      enjoyment now, when she had a little champagne in her head. It was natural
      that he should make love to her, with all the vulgarity of a cheap
      conqueror. Minna was used to the game. It pleased her to practise her arts
      of seduction. She knew that the caressing languor of her voice intoxicated
      the listener. He was the latest of innumerable wayfarers to whom she had
      held out the charmed cup. That she despised him added cynical zest.
      Besides, her own blood was stirred. A wanton woman does not turn men to
      swine for the mere fun of seeing them pigs. Boissy was in the slough of
      delight. His bad little face coarsened, his lips grew thick, his cheeks
      puffed up towards his eyes; he suggested a satyr debased by a civilised
      ancestry. In his mind, he was already bragging about his conquest to his
      friends.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish I had dared entertain you in a private room,&rdquo; he said, leaning
      over the table.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You would have sacrificed a great deal of gratification,&rdquo; replied Minna.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;How? We should have been alone.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You would not have satisfied your vanity,&rdquo; said Minna. &ldquo;You know that
      very well.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He protested. He was burning with adoration. She was cruel, like all her
      countrywomen.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have had enough good fortune for one day, I consider,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Ah, then, can I hope?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;That&rsquo;s a thing forbidden to no one,&rdquo; she replied, looking at him through
      her eyelashes.
    </p>
    <p>
      They had sat long over the meal. She expressed a desire for the outer air,
      and they strolled again together through the wonderful gardens. Behind
      them rose the great white palace of the casino, its marble balustrades and
      stairs and cupolas gleaming amidst the gorgeous vegetation. In front, the
      cobalt-blue Mediterranean meeting afar off the violet sky. On the left
      swept the fair Italian coast. On the right rose the black crag of Monaco,
      with its palace guarding the russet roofs of the little old town. Beneath
      them, terrace after terrace of greensward bedded with riotous profusion of
      flowers, broken by white parapets and flights of stairs. The scent of
      exotic flowers hung sensuously on the warm air.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It is intoxicating like wine, or your beauty,&rdquo; said Boissy.
    </p>
    <p>
      Minna shrugged her shoulders and glanced idly round.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a pretty place. But one gets tired of it, as of most things. What&rsquo;s
      the time?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Half-past two,&rdquo; he replied, consulting his watch.
    </p>
    <p>
      Mrs. Delamere would be there by half-past four. Then she could dismiss
      Boissy, of whom she was growing weary.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Shall we sit down? One talks better.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He indicated a sheltered seat behind some great aloes, and led her
      thither. Minna commanded him to amuse her.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am too much in love.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Then tell me the history of your last grand passion.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I have only had one in my life.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He began to plead. Somehow the charm of enticing him had palled. He was
      such a vulgar little creature. She had heard all he had to say scores of
      times. She craved originality. The sublime conceit of the man, who was
      growing earnestly amorous, moved her disdain. Unscrupulous and conscious
      of degradation as she was, she nevertheless set a great value on herself.
      So she found entertainment in scathing ridicule. At last he lost his
      temper, threw his arms roughly round her and kissed her. She struggled
      from him, revolted, and struck him with all her might in the face. The
      brutality of the debased Gaul was aroused. The crimson mark flared across
      a livid cheek. Mad with rage he seized her wrists.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Hallo!&rdquo; said a sudden voice. &ldquo;Drop that!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      A great, huge-limbed Englishman, dressed in loose tweeds and a discoloured
      straw hat, stood before them. Boissy rose to his feet and struck an
      attitude. &ldquo;Monsieur&mdash;&rdquo; he began.
    </p>
    <p>
      But the new-comer took no notice of him. Instead, he looked with an air of
      startled recognition at Minna, and then lifted his hat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Miss Hart, I believe.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The surprise was great. She regarded him for some moments rather
      bewildered. He seemed to have dropped from the sky.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Mr. Merriam!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      She collected herself quickly, rose, extended her hand. &ldquo;I am so glad to
      see you again,&rdquo; she said, with an air of sincerity warranted by the
      occasion.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Can I be of any service to you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, no, thanks,&rdquo; she replied lightly. And turning to Boissy, who stood by
      fuming, &ldquo;I have the pleasure of thanking you for a most agreeable
      afternoon.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      With a bow she dismissed him. He saluted with as good a grace as he could,
      including Gerard in his salute. But Gerard kept his hands in his pockets
      and watched him move away.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What the deuce was he trying to do?&rdquo; he asked.
 </p>
    <p>
&ldquo;Make love to me, I
      suppose.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Somewhat fiercely!&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I had just struck him across the face.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Are those the habits of these parts?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, no. We are tame as a rule. I had just been lunching with him in the
      most civilised way.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Perhaps I intruded,&rdquo; said Gerard.
 </p>
    <p>
&ldquo;By no means. You came just in time,
      like the hero in a melodrama, to save maiden innocence from the clutches
      of the villain.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;May I enjoy the hero&rsquo;s privilege of consolation?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Within moderate limits,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;I shall not be taking you from your
      friends?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, no. I don&rsquo;t expect my friend, Mrs. Delamere, who lives with me, till
      half-past four. Till then I am a waif. Shall we sit? Or, no. Let us find a
      place somewhere else.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      They walked together to the terrace below, and sat down facing the blue
      glory of the sea. On their way thither, she began to explain her presence
      in Monte Carlo. Nice had been her winter quarters for over three years.
      Her little villa was charming. If Mr. Merriam happened to be in Nice and
      would call at the Casa Benedetta, Mrs. Delamere and herself would be
      delighted to see him. Minna used her chaperon freely as a stalking horse
      of respectability.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I shall be glad to come,&rdquo; said Gerard, with an appreciative glance at his
      companion. &ldquo;I only landed in Europe yesterday, after a long absence, so I
      haven&rsquo;t found my bearings yet.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Where have you been?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Until lately in South Africa. Hunting and gold mining. Then I satisfied a
      schoolboy craze to see Madagascar. I don&rsquo;t want to see it again. Was down
      with fever most of the time, and took the first Messageries steamer to
      Marseilles. Then I thought I would put in a week or two here, before
      facing the wretched English spring.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;So you&rsquo;ve been gold-mining,&rdquo; said Minna.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes. Pretty successfully. Came in just before the boom.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Made a fortune?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve cleared a tidy bit.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;And you&rsquo;ve come here to dispose of some of it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;At the tables? Not much. I am not that sort.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I am afraid I am,&rdquo; said Minna, with a little sigh.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Do you win or lose?&rdquo; he asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Last year I lost £6,000. This year I am winning. That&rsquo;s one reason why I
      live in these parts. The tables are a necessity to me. Monte Carlo,
      Aix-les-Bains, Ostend. That&rsquo;s my usual round.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Don&rsquo;t you get rather sick of it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      Minna looked mournfully out to sea, and clasped her hands in her lap. A
      pathetic attitude, somewhat out of harmony with the daffodil toilette and
      the unblushing hat.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Pleasures would be tolerable were it not that one has to live so as to
      enjoy them,&rdquo; she said, after a pause.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have come by your pessimism early in life,&rdquo; he observed.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I&rsquo;ve not had much to encourage optimism, as you may be aware, Mr.
      Merriam.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You had a bad bout, of course. So did we all,&rdquo; said Gerard. &ldquo;But you have
      had time to recover.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What are you going to do with your money?&rdquo; she asked.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh&mdash;I don&rsquo;t know. Buy an estate in my own county&mdash;Norfolk&mdash;and
      settle down to squiredom. Breed stock and preserve pheasants and that sort
      of thing.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Will you be glad to get back?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I suppose so. Every one is, in a way. Wouldn&rsquo;t you?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I loathe England and all that it contains too much,&rdquo; she said with
      bitterness. &ldquo;And I can&rsquo;t understand your wanting to return, either.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      The first allusion to past events was followed by a short silence, during
      which each took mental stock of the other. The circumstances in which they
      had met had led naturally to a false assumption of friendliness. Now each
      was abruptly reminded of the very distant acquaintance that had existed
      between them, and of the strange part each had played in the other&rsquo;s life.
      Minna&rsquo;s expansion had been due to gratitude to him for having effectually
      rid her of Boissy, and to the novelty of talking to a big, lumbering
      Englishman.
    </p>
    <p>
      Realising, however, who he was, she shrank within herself. A queer cold
      touch, which she could not explain, pressed around her heart. She had felt
      it before. Once, on the night, three years ago, when she had seen Hugh and
      Irene at the Haymarket Theatre. She moved slightly away from him with a
      sense of dislike. And yet his blunt, indifferent manner of speech pricked
      her vanity. He had thrown an admiring glance neither upon herself nor her
      costume. He should pay her some kind of homage whether she disliked him or
      not.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;It&rsquo;s funny my tumbling upon you like that,&rdquo; he remarked at last.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;We generally choose dramatic moments for our interviews,&rdquo; said Minna
      cynically.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Yes, by Jove. The last one seems a long time ago, doesn&rsquo;t it?&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Not to me,&rdquo; said Minna. &ldquo;But then, you see, I haven&rsquo;t been gold-hunting
      at the ends of the earth. I&rsquo;ve been living rapidly round a roulette-board.
      I suppose you know that the mystery of my poor father&rsquo;s death was cleared
      up.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I saw it in the Cape papers. I was very glad.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      There was another pause. Minna broke its discomfort by a casual allusion
      to the beauties of Monte Carlo.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;You have nothing like this in South Africa,&rdquo; she said.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;I wish we had,&rdquo; he replied. &ldquo;If things were always as jolly as this, I
      should never want to get out of Europe.&rdquo;
     </p>
    <p>
      He stretched himself out in a comfortable attitude, and looked contentedly
      at his companion. The talk drifted into generalities. Minna whetted upon
      him her satiric knife, a process which he found himself to be enjoying.
      The Jew money-lender&rsquo;s daughter, the rather common and silly little girl,
      whom he once despised, appeared to him in a totally new light. She had
      developed into a beautiful woman, with a cynical knowledge of the world
      and an alluring shamelessness of speech. Her manner was that of the
      insolently luxurious demi-mondaine; her great wealth transferred her to
      the sphere of the unassailed. In this dual, interfused light, she appeared
      a woman well worth the study of an idle afternoon. She was certainly a
      change from the fair frailties of South Africa. The puffs and frills and
      ribbons of the daring daffodil costume struck an elementary note of sex.
      He began to forget that she had mopped and mowed at him like an imbecile
      when they had last been face to face. She was a new acquaintance. He found
      himself losing the brusqueness of his earlier words, and dropping into the
      tone of deference her languid beauty seemed to command. When she arose, in
      the intention of going to meet Mrs. Delamere&rsquo;s train, and held out her
      hand for farewell, he offered his escort to the railway station, with the
      air of a man begging for a favour. Minna was amused, somewhat interested;
      the originality of the situation gave a fillip to her mood. She assented
      graciously, and they proceeded through the casino grounds.
    </p>
    <p>
      They arrived at the station a minute or two before the train. Mrs.
      Delamere stepped out on to the platform. Minna with a strange man at her
      heels was by no means an unusual sight. But when Minna introduced him as
      her old friend, Mr. Merriam, she arched her eyebrows involuntarily, and
      glanced at the girl, in whose eyes gleamed a spark of mockery.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;What has become of M. de Boissy?&rdquo; she asked on their way to the casino.
    </p>
    <p>
      &ldquo;Oh, Mr. Merriam told him to go and play,&rdquo; laughed Minna.
    </p>
    <p>
      <br /><br />
    </p>
